    {"question_text": "What does this TTL cache implementation do?\\n\\nimport time\\nfrom functools import wraps\\n\\ndef ttl_cache(ttl_seconds=60):\\n    def decorator(func):\\n        cache = {}\\n        @wraps(func)\\n        def wrapper(*args):\\n            now = time.time()\\n            if args in cache:\\n                result, timestamp = cache[args]\\n                if now - timestamp < ttl_seconds:\\n                    return result\\n            result = func(*args)\\n            cache[args] = (result, now)\\n            return result\\n        return wrapper\\n    return decorator\\n\\n@ttl_cache(ttl_seconds=30)\\ndef get_user(user_id):\\n    return db_query(user_id)", "option_a": "Caches forever like lru_cache", "option_b": "Clears entire cache every 30 seconds", "option_c": "Caches results for 30 seconds; stale entries are recomputed on next access after TTL expires", "option_d": "Only caches the first call, never updates", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "performance_optimization"},
