    {"question_text": "What does this precomputation pattern optimize?\\n\\nimport math\\n\\n# Slow: computes sin/cos every iteration\\ndef rotate_points_slow(points, angle):\\n    results = []\\n    for x, y in points:\\n        new_x = x * math.cos(angle) - y * math.sin(angle)\\n        new_y = x * math.sin(angle) + y * math.cos(angle)\\n        results.append((new_x, new_y))\\n    return results\\n\\n# Fast: compute sin/cos once\\ndef rotate_points_fast(points, angle):\\n    cos_a = math.cos(angle)\\n    sin_a = math.sin(angle)\\n    return [(x * cos_a - y * sin_a, x * sin_a + y * cos_a) for x, y in points]\\n\\n# For 1 million points, what is the difference?", "option_a": "No difference - Python optimizes repeated function calls", "option_b": "Slow version is faster due to branch prediction", "option_c": "Fast version calls math.cos/sin once instead of 2M times; eliminates redundant computation and function call overhead", "option_d": "Both make the same number of function calls", "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "advanced", "topic": "performance_optimization"},
